		<p class="text">
			<b>Law for the effective use of renewable energy (LAERFTE):</b> LAERFTE was implemented in 2012 to promote the growth and development of renewable energy in the country.  This law obliges CFE (a government-owned utility that controls and monitors the country’s entire energy grid) to buy electricity produced from any and all private and public renewable energy projects under 30 MW. This recently implemented law offers business opportunities for foreign and domestic investment in the renewable energy industry.
		</p>

		<p class="text">
			<b>Net-Metering:</b> Allows residential and commercial clean energy producers to store excess electricity produced in the energy grid as credit for a period of one year. If a residential customer has a PV system that generates more electricity than their home uses, the excess electricity will be stored as credit and it can be used to compensate for low electric production at certain times of the day or year.
		</p>

		<p class="text">
			<b>Energy Portage:</b> Allows residential and commercial energy producers to input electricity to the grid and use it anywhere in the country. This mechanism maximizes each technology’s capabilities by allowing   projects to be constructed in locations that are ideal to each technology regardless of where the consumer is located. A company that produces clean energy in Southern Mexico can consume the equivalent amount of electricity anywhere in the country.
		</p>

